framework_groups_array.name: Drivers
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Drivers are an initial factor or a set of factors that (can) trigger or expose to suffering or life-threatening conditions. Aggravating factors are contextual elements that exacerbate the crisis, such as pre-existing food insecurity, lack of governance capacity, hazard-prone conditions, gender inequalities, social discrimination, remoteness

framework_groups_array.name: Damages & Losses
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Damages: Information about total or partial destruction of infrastructure and physical assets existing in the affected area. For example, number of buildings, education and health facilities, government buildings, community infrastructure, etc.   Losses: outcomes arising from “damages”, such as loss in revenues due to damage to livelihood assets, or direct loss of property, such as loss of documentation due to displacement or flooding.

framework_groups_array.name: Status of essential infrastructure, systems, markets and networks
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Disruption of infrastructure, systems, markets or networks impacting service delivery. For example, any disruption to services such as education, social security, housing or health care, whether provided by the public or the private sector.

framework_groups_array.name: Living Standards
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Direct consequences related to access, availability, awareness, use and quality of basic/essential goods and services. For example, % of children with access to safe learning space, number of doctors per 1.000 patients, etc. These are sometimes referred to as first level humanitarian outcomes.

framework_groups_array.name: Coping Mechanisms
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Also referred to as coping strategies, these are activities adopted by people, organizations and systems, using available skills and resources, to manage adverse conditions, risk or disasters.  Information on coping mechanisms generally pertains to negative activities (e.g. selling off assets to buy food), but may also be positive.

framework_groups_array.name: Physical and mental well-being
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Direct impact on an individual’s physical or mental health, which may result from first level outcomes (e.g. prolonged lack of access to food resulting in death due to undernutrition), or incidents (eg. a security incident resulting in injury).There are sometimes referred to as second level humanitarian outcomes.

framework_groups_array.name: Persons/groups with Specific Needs
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Population groups that may be particularly vulnerable due to gender, age or chronic disability and are entitled to special assistance. Girls and boys, including unaccompanied or separated children, persons with serious chronic illnesses, elderly, persons with disabilities, female headed-households and persons with a diverse sexual orientation or gender identity are generally considered to have specific needs. It is important to keep in mind that not every individual in these groups will have specific needs and that these needs may alter over time depending on context.

framework_groups_array.name: Risks &  new or aggravated vulnerabilities
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Situations that could potentially catalyse or deteriorate first and second level outcomes, if needs are not addressed. Risk is defined as a function of hazard, exposure, vulnerability and capacity and should be related to a specific event, timeframe and system.

framework_groups_array.name: Number of people in need and priorities
International
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Combination of strengths and resources of international stakeholders to respond to a crisis in theory (capacities) or mechanisms actually being deployed to respond to an ongoing crisis (response)

framework_groups_array.name: National and local
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Combination of strengths and resources of national and/or local stakeholders (government or local NGOs) to respond to a crisis in theory (capacities) or mechanisms actually being deployed to respond to an ongoing crisis (response)

framework_groups_array.name: Community
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Combination of strengths and resources of the community in the affected geolocation to respond to a crisis in theory (capacities) or mechanisms actually being deployed to respond to an ongoing crisis (response)

framework_groups_array.name: Community perceived priorities
framework_groups_array.tooltip: Community’s perspective on required/preferred response interventions and priorities

sector_array.tooltip: Information related to shelter and households items

sector_array.tooltip: Information related to the WASH sector, including Water supply, hygiene, sanitation, waste management and vector control
